An invaluable symptoms-self-reporting App to defeat COVID-19! (originally 26/04/2020) .............................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. PS (10/05/2020): Please fix the American MM-DD-YYYY by changing it back to the UK DD-MM-YYYY! A VERY unforgivable error (and I unfortunately would have to take one Star off, I am afraid) ! Would also like to see an option for (other) users to declare 'Chinese (China)', 'Chinese (any other background)', 'Other East Asians' (e.g. Japanese or Koreans), 'South East Asians' (S.E.A.), and 'South Pacific Islanders', although I do understand that the demographics in terms of presence in the United Kingdom might well be too limited to justify creating too many other additional categories. I am happy to declare myself as a Chinese (on this very occasion for this very specific purpose, but not otherwise), but NOT 'British Chinese', because the term 'British Chinese' is coined by UK political organisations and is NOT REALLY used by the Chinese communities (notice: plural, not singular) here in the UK, by themselves, and is anyway also not an appropriate term in terms of collecting the actual ethnic background of the user for HEALTH purposes, rather than one of simple ethnic diversity/equal opportunities monitoring/'box-ticking exercise' for the purpose of the Equality Act 2010. The term 'Chinese' is also a political term unfortunately, and there are e.g. Malaysians (e.g. Malaysian students or student doctors, or trainee pharmacists) in the UK with a Chinese-Malaysian background who might perhaps be more happy to participate if they are allowed to more explicitly declare to the effect that "they have a Chinese background but not of a direct (i.e., recent) Chinese origin" (i.e., "Chinese (any other background)") (in some cases, a lot if not all of their ancestors had left China sometime before the start of WW2; and in some rarer cases before 1900).
